etymologies: mid 18th century; earliest use found in Roger North (1651–1734), lawyer, politician, and writer. From un- + qualifiable

definitions: Lacking the attributes or accomplishments required to qualify for something; incapable of attaining the necessary qualifications.
That cannot be characterized as having specific qualities; indefinable; indescribable.

notes.text: Common in the 19th century. Now rare.

definitions: That cannot be modified, limited, or restricted; not open to qualification.
